The paper deals with the problem of reliable multiparty computation in the presence of an adversary, which is a common topic in the field of cryptography and security (cs.CR). The algorithm described in the paper involves performing computations repeatedly as inputs change, which suggests a distributed computing aspect (cs.DC). The paper also mentions the resource costs and latency of the algorithm, which are important considerations in the design of distributed systems (cs.DS). The use of computational operations and expected number of corruptions suggests an information theory aspect (cs.IT). Finally, the paper mentions the properties of the circuit that computes the function, which could be relevant to machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.LG).
